\par }{\cgrid0 The Diagnostics and Statistics Manual [}{American Psychiatric Association. DSM-IV. 4th Ed. Washington}{\cgrid0 , 1994] defines "personality" as:
\par }{\i\cgrid0 "...enduring patterns of perceiving, relating to, and thinking about the environment and oneself... exhibited in a wide range of important social and personal contexts."}{\i 
\par }{\cgrid0 It defines personality disorders as:}{
\par }{\b\cgrid0 A.}{\cgrid0  An enduring pattern of inner experience and behaviour that deviates markedly from the expectations of the individual's culture. This pattern is manifested in two (or more) of the following areas:
\par }\pard \qj \fi-227\li397\ri0\sl264\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin397\itap0 {a.\tab Cognition (i.e., ways of perceiving and interpreting self, other people, and events);
\par }{\cgrid0 b.\tab Affectivity (i.e., the range, intensity, lability, and appropriateness of emotional response);}{
\par }{\cgrid0 c.\tab Interpersonal functioning;}{
\par }{\cgrid0 d.\tab Impulse control.}{
\par }\pard \qj \fi170\li0\ri0\sl264\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\cgrid0 B.}{\cgrid0  The enduring pattern is inflexible and pervasive across a broad range of personal and social situations.}{
\par }{\b\cgrid0 C.}{\cgrid0  The enduring pattern leads to clinically significant distress or impairment in social, occupational, or other important areas of functioning.}{
\par }{\b\cgrid0 D.}{\cgrid0  The pattern is stable and of long duration, and its onset can be traced back at least to adolescence or early adulthood.}{
\par }{\b\cgrid0 E.}{\cgrid0  The enduring pattern is not better accounted for as a manifestation or consequence of another mental disorder.}{
\par }{\b\cgrid0 F. }{\cgrid0 The enduring pattern is not due to the direct physiological effects of a substance (e.g., a drug abuse, a medication) or a general medical condition (e.g., head trauma).}{
\par }{\fs16\cgrid0 [}{\fs16 American Psychiatric Association. Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders: DSM-IV. 4th ed. Washington, 1994}{\fs16\cgrid0 ]
